(7)

HCN reacts with the ∙OH radicals to form cyanide radicals (∙CN)

HCN + ∙OH ∙CN + H2O

(8)

which are then oxidised to the isocyanate radical (∙NCO) by OH∙ and O2

∙CN + ∙OH  ∙NCO + H∙

(9)

∙CN + O2  ∙NCO + ∙O∙

(10)

The isocyanate radical then combines with ∙O∙ to form nitric oxide (NO) and CO (11), or with nitric oxide

to form N2O, N2, CO and CO2 (12 and 13). Nitric oxide is a stable free radical which exists as a gas at room

temperature.

∙NCO + ∙O∙ ∙NO + CO

(11)

Or with nitric oxide to form N2O, N2, CO and CO2

∙NCO + ∙NO N2O + CO

(12)

∙NCO + ∙NO N2 + CO2

(13)

At atmospheric pressure between 800-1100° C, the main attack on HCN comes from OH∙ radicals via

reactions 8, 14 and 15.

HCN + ∙OH HOCN + H∙

(14)

HCN + ∙OH HNCO + H∙

(15)

Reactions 8, 14 and 15 are important under all conditions, whereas reactions 16 and 17 involving ∙O∙ and

H∙ (forming ∙CN and hydrogen isocyanide) are only significant under fuel rich conditions [23].

HCN + ∙O∙

∙CN + H2O

(16)

HCN + M or H∙ HNC + M or H∙

(17)

This mechanism underlines the critical role played by the ∙OH radical in the oxidation of HCN, particularly

in well-ventilated conditions.

The current work describes the effects of two gas phase flame retardant systems on the CO and HCN yields of a burning polyamide in well ventilated conditions where, because of the presence of flame quenchers, the toxicity is significant. Moreover, it goes on to explain why these two flame retardant systems have contrasting effects, based on published information describing the fire retardancy mechanisms.

EXPERIMENTAL

Sample preparation

Three materials were investigated. They were based on polyamide 6.6. All materials were reinforced with 30 wt% glass fibre. This glass fibre composite will be referred to as PA/GF. The glass fibre composites were flame retarded using industry standard formulations containing either a blend of aluminium phosphinate and melamine polyphosphate (collectively abbreviated to P-N FR) or brominated polystyrene and antimony oxide (abbreviated to Sb-Br FR). All the flame retardant samples were formulated to meet UL-94 V-0 at 0.8 mm. In practice, this required a total flame retardant loading of 20 wt% for the PA/GF/P-

